NOTE: All readings taken from Changi climate station What is La Nina?
La Nina is a natural climate phenomenon that affects the weather over the maritime continent, which includes Singapore and Indonesia. La Nina causes more rainy weather and is affecting Singapore now. Warm ocean surface temperatur­es Cooler ocean surface temperatur­es Wind direction Normal conditions
The westward-blowing trade winds lead to cold water upwelling in the equatorial eastern Pacific Ocean. Western Pacific Ocean AUSTRALIA Westward-blowing trade winds intensify during a La Nina event, causing more warm water to pool around the maritime continent. Western Pacific Ocean Eastern Pacific Ocean AUSTRALIA Jan 2 0 0 0 0 32. 2 0.8 Warm shallow layer Cold deep layer SOUTH AMERICA Cold deep layer SOUTH AMERICA What is a monsoon surge? • The uptick in rainfall and cool temperatur­es in the past few days are caused by a monsoon surge. • Such a surge refers to a strengthen­ing of winds over the South China Sea, causing extensive rain clouds to form over Singapore and its surroundin­g region. • This might lead to more intensive rainfall, over prolonged periods of time.
